    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3624597556" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3624597556" />
    <a title="Trevor Cook" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32774855-trevor-cook"><img alt="Trevor Cook" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1576547045p2/32774855.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3624597556?book_show_action=true">Dec 03, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Trevor Cook" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Trevor Cook" href="/user/show/32774855-trevor-cook">Trevor Cook</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3624597556" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9386959803559543800">Incredible book. This is such a different sort of disaster than Rob Hall’s expedition on Everest in 1996. When you attempt the tallest peak in the world, you voluntarily take the risk of injury or death and regardless expect to gain a spectacular experience. Nando Parrado and those on the flight with him didn’t sign up for a death defying experience, but those were the cards life dealt them. <br/>I love Nando’s portrayal of the events that took place as well. He finds something kind to say about ever</span>
  <span id="freeText9386959803559543800" style="display:none">Incredible book. This is such a different sort of disaster than Rob Hall’s expedition on Everest in 1996. When you attempt the tallest peak in the world, you voluntarily take the risk of injury or death and regardless expect to gain a spectacular experience. Nando Parrado and those on the flight with him didn’t sign up for a death defying experience, but those were the cards life dealt them. <br />I love Nando’s portrayal of the events that took place as well. He finds something kind to say about every person present and humbly recognizes his own faults. He doesn’t romanticize his or any one else’s actions. The story is simply an account of what happened and what was going through his mind at the time. <br />Throughout the book, I kept thinking about what I would do in their place. I want to believe that I would be one of the ones helping others and attempting brave feats, but who am I to say what I would do when I’ve never experienced anything remotely like this? Without giving any spoilers, it takes true courage and resilience to do some of the stuff those boys had to do to survive. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9386959803559543800" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


